WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.190 --> 00:00:09.310
JESSE MICHELS: Welcome,
everybody, to Talks at Google.

00:00:09.310 --> 00:00:10.760
We are so happy
to have you here.

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:14.590
We're very happy to have our
guest here, our esteemed guest,

00:00:14.590 --> 00:00:16.270
Scooter Braun.

00:00:16.270 --> 00:00:19.600
Scooter is one of the biggest
entrepreneurs and innovators

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:22.030
in entertainment today.

00:00:22.030 --> 00:00:25.020
He started as a
teenage party promoter.

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:28.420
He was the biggest college
party promoter in Atlanta

00:00:28.420 --> 00:00:29.350
while going to Emory.

00:00:29.350 --> 00:00:32.020
He leveraged that into a
director of marketing position

00:00:32.020 --> 00:00:34.420
at So So Def in its heyday.

00:00:34.420 --> 00:00:38.020
He left So So Def, found
a little-known artist

00:00:38.020 --> 00:00:41.590
named Justin Bieber, and
then basically leveraged that

00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:45.910
into creating the largest,
or one of the largest media

00:00:45.910 --> 00:00:49.600
empires in music and
entertainment today.

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:51.910
SB Projects covers all media.

00:00:51.910 --> 00:00:53.680
It's not just music.

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:57.610
So he obviously manages artists
like Kanye West, Ariana Grande,

00:00:57.610 --> 00:01:02.510
Justin Bieber, of course,
EDM acts like Martin Garrix

00:01:02.510 --> 00:01:05.760
and then models
like Karlie Kloss.

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:08.710
It also has a tech incubator
arm called Silent Labs.

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:10.390
We were just talking
about it earlier.

00:01:10.390 --> 00:01:13.750
They have really impressive
investments in Uber, Spotify,

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:15.530
Waze, Pinterest, to name a few.

00:01:15.530 --> 00:01:18.850
So his track record there
is pretty impressive.

00:01:18.850 --> 00:01:20.800
And he's also all
about giving back.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:22.990
So he's on the
board of directors

00:01:22.990 --> 00:01:26.110
of his brother's foundation,
Pencils of Promise, as well

00:01:26.110 --> 00:01:28.185
as his wife's foundation.

00:01:28.185 --> 00:01:30.310
And I don't think we're
allowed to curse here, so--

00:01:30.310 --> 00:01:31.435
SCOOTER BRAUN: Fuck Cancer.

00:01:31.435 --> 00:01:32.650
- There you go.

00:01:32.650 --> 00:01:33.615
He went for it.

00:01:33.615 --> 00:01:34.990
SCOOTER BRAUN: I
don't work here.

00:01:34.990 --> 00:01:38.620
- And that's his wife, Yael
Braun, also very impressive

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:39.610
in her own right.

00:01:39.610 --> 00:01:41.740
Please give it up
for Scooter Braun.

00:01:41.740 --> 00:01:43.066
Thank you so much for coming.

00:01:43.066 --> 00:01:48.122
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:48.122 --> 00:01:49.080
JESSE MICHELS: Awesome.

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:51.800
So I actually want to
start with your childhood

00:01:51.800 --> 00:01:53.090
and just set a little context.

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:57.144
And I want to start with a
movie you made, a student film.

00:01:57.144 --> 00:01:59.060
When you were in high
school, you made a movie

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:00.680
about the Jews of Hungary.

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:03.549
And this had a special kind
of place in your heritage.

00:02:03.549 --> 00:02:05.090
And you actually
got some recognition

00:02:05.090 --> 00:02:07.610
from Steven Spielberg
on it, is that correct?

00:02:07.610 --> 00:02:10.400
Can you tell us that story?

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:14.180
SCOOTER BRAUN: I went to school,
and my teacher in middle school

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:16.790
said, there's something
called National History Day.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:20.150
And no one from our school
has ever gotten to nationals.

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:21.650
But if you get to
nationals, there's

00:02:21.650 --> 00:02:24.320
an all-expense paid
trip to Washington DC.

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:26.370
And I really wanted to
go to Washington DC.

00:02:26.370 --> 00:02:27.620
I wanted to see the monuments.

00:02:27.620 --> 00:02:30.694
I wanted to see everything
I'd seen about it.

00:02:30.694 --> 00:02:32.360
So I went home that
day and I said, Mom,

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:33.697
I'm going to Washington DC.

00:02:33.697 --> 00:02:35.030
And then she said, you're crazy.

00:02:35.030 --> 00:02:36.571
She goes, what are
you talking about?

00:02:36.571 --> 00:02:37.960
And I came up with this idea.

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:39.860
So my grandparents are
Holocaust survivors.

00:02:39.860 --> 00:02:42.350
My grandmother was liberated
from Bergen-Belsen,

00:02:42.350 --> 00:02:46.100
was in Auschwitz, and my
grandfather was in Dachau.

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:49.400
And I was always
kind of fascinated

00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:52.280
by the story of how they could
just live in this country

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:54.950
and live a normal life like
I was living at the time.

00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:57.260
And then suddenly, their
country just betrays them

00:02:57.260 --> 00:02:59.730
and everyone in their
family dies and they

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:01.700
are the only survivors.

00:03:01.700 --> 00:03:04.400
So I decided to do a
10-minute documentary called

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:06.020
"The Hungarian Conflict."

00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:09.770
And it was the story of how
hundreds of thousands of Jews

00:03:09.770 --> 00:03:12.050
were deported over
two weeks voluntarily

00:03:12.050 --> 00:03:14.540
by the German people
and the German army

00:03:14.540 --> 00:03:17.510
towards the end of the war.

00:03:17.510 --> 00:03:22.850
And I submitted it, won
regionals, won states.

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:26.240
Lost in nationals to a
documentary about airplanes

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:30.290
that make loud noises and fly
over a neighborhood in Chicago,

00:03:30.290 --> 00:03:33.280
because that is the most
important topic that can beat

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:35.136
a story about the Holocaust.

00:03:35.136 --> 00:03:35.760
I'm not bitter.

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:36.440
I'm 36.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:37.450
I've let go of it.

00:03:37.450 --> 00:03:39.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:39.390 --> 00:03:41.100
But actually, I had
an amazing time.

00:03:41.100 --> 00:03:41.800
I got to go down there.

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:42.800
I made a lot of friends.

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:46.020
And I was 13, 14 years old.

00:03:46.020 --> 00:03:50.070
And when I came back, my other
grandmother, my mom's mother,

00:03:50.070 --> 00:03:52.790
she was very proud, and she sent
it into the Holocaust Museum.

00:03:52.790 --> 00:03:56.640
And somehow, someone got
it to Steven Spielberg.

00:03:56.640 --> 00:03:58.640
She had sent it to his
office and everyone else,

00:03:58.640 --> 00:03:59.810
because he had the
Shoah Foundation.

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:02.101
He was collecting information
about Holocaust survivors

00:04:02.101 --> 00:04:03.170
at the time.

00:04:03.170 --> 00:04:05.455
And I had no contact
to entertainment.

00:04:05.455 --> 00:04:07.580
No one in my family had a
contact to entertainment.

00:04:07.580 --> 00:04:10.880
We knew no one in the
world I now work in.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:13.070
And one day in the
mail, I get this letter

00:04:13.070 --> 00:04:15.350
from the office of
Steven Spielberg.

00:04:15.350 --> 00:04:19.010
And a letter typed
out on his letterhead

00:04:19.010 --> 00:04:21.740
signed by him,
talking about my film

00:04:21.740 --> 00:04:23.780
and encouraging
me to keep going.

00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:26.741
And I framed it and it's
been on my wall ever since.

00:04:26.741 --> 00:04:28.490
When I went to college,
it was on my wall.

00:04:28.490 --> 00:04:31.520
It's on the wall in
my home office now.

00:04:31.520 --> 00:04:34.890
And it made me believe that I
could really achieve anything.

00:04:34.890 --> 00:04:36.440
Like, if a kid who
had no contacts

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:41.810
could get to Steven Spielberg,
I thought anything is possible.

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:47.510
And funny enough,
about 17 years later,

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:50.030
I was at the White House
press dinner with a client.

00:04:50.030 --> 00:04:53.270
And they moved us
into a private room

00:04:53.270 --> 00:04:55.880
with celebrities, because
they didn't want the press

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:58.160
just hounding these
celebrities in the big room

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:02.330
before the event with
the president started.

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:03.980
And Steven Spielberg
was in the room

00:05:03.980 --> 00:05:05.389
and he started talking to us.

00:05:05.389 --> 00:05:06.180
And I said, listen.

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:07.721
I don't mean to
interrupt, but I just

00:05:07.721 --> 00:05:09.590
need to tell you years
ago when I was a kid,

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:11.510
I did a video about
the Holocaust.

00:05:11.510 --> 00:05:13.343
And you-- and before I
could get a word out,

00:05:13.343 --> 00:05:15.960
he goes, you didn't do the
Hungarian one, did you?

00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:18.950
And he remembered,
17 years later.

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:20.960
And I was completely in shock.

00:05:20.960 --> 00:05:24.566
And it's just a testament to
who he is and how genuine he is.

00:05:24.566 --> 00:05:25.940
And it was just
very encouraging.

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:29.605
I still have it on
my wall to this day.

00:05:29.605 --> 00:05:31.980
JESSE MICHELS: You mentioned
something pretty remarkable,

00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:33.521
which is that you
started off knowing

00:05:33.521 --> 00:05:34.640
no one in entertainment.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:37.440
Now you know everybody
in entertainment.

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:40.550
So if the first inflection point
was Steven Spielberg giving you

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:44.570
recognition and that giving
you just the belief in yourself

00:05:44.570 --> 00:05:47.510
to do anything after that,
a second inflection point

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:49.710
is cut to Atlanta.

00:05:49.710 --> 00:05:51.590
You're throwing
parties for rappers

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:52.790
like Ludacris and Eminem.

00:05:52.790 --> 00:05:57.380
How exactly did that come about?

00:05:57.380 --> 00:06:01.190
SCOOTER BRAUN:
Atlanta was racist.

00:06:01.190 --> 00:06:04.630
And that's the
reason it happened.

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:07.444
I went down to Atlanta
to play basketball

00:06:07.444 --> 00:06:08.860
and broke my dad's
heart because I

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:13.130
took a D3 offer instead of a
D1 offer, because D1 said, hi.

00:06:13.130 --> 00:06:17.080
You're 5'11" and can't
really jump or run that fast.

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:17.831
So nice jump shot.

00:06:17.831 --> 00:06:20.080
You're going to sit the bench
for the first two years.

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:21.559
And I didn't really like that.

00:06:21.559 --> 00:06:23.350
So I was like, OK, I'm
going to go play D3.

00:06:23.350 --> 00:06:26.544
I'm going to come out and
start to get playing time.

00:06:26.544 --> 00:06:28.960
And I got down to Atlanta and
no one cared about our team.

00:06:28.960 --> 00:06:31.417
And my best friend
was at Duke, and he

00:06:31.417 --> 00:06:32.500
was the star of that team.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:35.620
And we played AAU basketball
against each other,

00:06:35.620 --> 00:06:37.020
so that's how we
knew each other.

00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:42.060
And when I got down there,
because I came from an AAU

00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:46.350
basketball team where I
was a minority on my team,

00:06:46.350 --> 00:06:49.290
I was one of three white guys on
a majority black baseball team.

00:06:49.290 --> 00:06:53.424
And our team-- since we were
14 years old in our state--

00:06:53.424 --> 00:06:55.590
every weekend, three to
four months out of the year,

00:06:55.590 --> 00:06:58.110
we were in hotel rooms
together as brothers.

00:06:58.110 --> 00:07:00.414
I mean, these guys are still
to this day my brothers.

00:07:00.414 --> 00:07:02.580
I have to explain to my
wife when one of them calls.

00:07:02.580 --> 00:07:03.960
Like, well I've never
even met this person.

00:07:03.960 --> 00:07:05.959
You're just going to let
him sleep in our house?

00:07:05.959 --> 00:07:10.322
And said, in my
childhood, this is family.

00:07:10.322 --> 00:07:12.030
So when I got to
Atlanta, I didn't really

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:14.550
have that perspective
of white people

00:07:14.550 --> 00:07:16.942
went to clubs that played
techno and black people when

00:07:16.942 --> 00:07:18.150
to clubs that played hip-hop.

00:07:18.150 --> 00:07:19.770
And there was no mixing.

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:24.780
So I didn't like that
and I saw an opening.

00:07:24.780 --> 00:07:30.030
And I needed legit money
because I was broke.

00:07:30.030 --> 00:07:36.000
And selling fake IDs was
not a long-term plan.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.984
So I stopped by this club
called Chaos in Buckhead

00:07:39.984 --> 00:07:40.650
back in the day.

00:07:40.650 --> 00:07:43.570
And I said, if you let me bring
people here, will you pay me?

00:07:43.570 --> 00:07:45.570
And he goes, well how
many people can you bring?

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:46.590
I said, how many do you hold?

00:07:46.590 --> 00:07:47.400
And he said, 800.

00:07:47.400 --> 00:07:49.020
I said, that sounds about right.

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:50.311
I didn't know what I was doing.

00:07:50.311 --> 00:07:51.720
I went to Kinko's,
I made flyers.

00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:53.320
I named my company
Kryptonite Entertainment

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:54.510
because I liked Superman.

00:07:54.510 --> 00:07:57.000
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.210
And I had a bunch
of freshmen girls

00:08:00.210 --> 00:08:03.330
pass out flyers for me, because
I had a high school sweetheart.

00:08:03.330 --> 00:08:05.820
So the freshman girls
weren't threatened by me

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:07.380
because I would
dance and have fun,

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:09.390
but I wasn't trying
to sleep with them

00:08:09.390 --> 00:08:12.210
because I was loyal to my
high school sweetheart.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:15.950
And where the freshmen
girls tell you to go,

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:19.380
it seems like the rest
of the campus went.

00:08:19.380 --> 00:08:22.370
And next thing you know,
I had 800 people there.

00:08:22.370 --> 00:08:25.880
And-- this is a long story,
but sorry for taking so long--

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:29.550
that first party, someone
approached me and he was like,

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:30.640
this party is amazing.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:33.205
Look at all these kids,
different diversity,

00:08:33.205 --> 00:08:34.080
listening to hip-hop.

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:34.913
And I looked at him.

00:08:34.913 --> 00:08:36.742
I was like, you're
Michael Jackson.

00:08:36.742 --> 00:08:38.200
And no, it was not
Michael Jackson.

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.530
But it was Jason Weaver,
who played young Michael

00:08:40.530 --> 00:08:42.701
Jackson in the VH1
movie that I would

00:08:42.701 --> 00:08:44.159
watch every single
year when they'd

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:46.290
play it about the Jacksons.

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:49.140
And he was like, yeah, I'm
on a different TV show now.

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:51.420
That was like 10
years ago, dude.

00:08:51.420 --> 00:08:54.267
And he said, do you want to
see how the other half lives?

00:08:54.267 --> 00:08:56.100
And I said, what do you
mean the other half?

00:08:56.100 --> 00:08:57.820
He goes, black people.

00:08:57.820 --> 00:09:02.510
And he took me to Velvet
Room on a Tuesday night.

00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:05.190
This guy remembers old Atlanta.

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:10.040
So the original Velvet Room.

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:13.800
And there was a guy named
Alex Gidewon, who is now

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:16.470
one of the biggest club owners
in Atlanta, who originally

00:09:16.470 --> 00:09:19.380
started off as an Ethiopian
immigrant parking lot

00:09:19.380 --> 00:09:20.280
attendant.

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:23.250
And at that point, he'd
become a huge promoter.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:25.300
And he had a
stutter, still does.

00:09:25.300 --> 00:09:29.040
And he was so fascinated
that I was there that he said

00:09:29.040 --> 00:09:33.129
l-l-l-l-l-let the white boy in.

00:09:33.129 --> 00:09:34.920
And he let me in for
free instead of paying

00:09:34.920 --> 00:09:38.610
the $100 a head cutline charge.

00:09:38.610 --> 00:09:42.270
And I would put parties on
every Thursday for college kids

00:09:42.270 --> 00:09:46.440
and spend every dollar of it
on Tuesdays meeting people.

00:09:46.440 --> 00:09:50.470
Basically faking
it till I made it.

00:09:50.470 --> 00:09:53.145
And then I made so much
cash with the parties

00:09:53.145 --> 00:09:55.020
because Alex really
taught me how to promote.

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:57.330
I learned what I really deserved
to make at those parties.

00:09:57.330 --> 00:09:59.163
I started making the
door a part of the bar.

00:09:59.163 --> 00:10:01.020
And he educated me.

00:10:01.020 --> 00:10:06.570
And I bought a purple Mercedes
with rims on eBay, cash.

00:10:06.570 --> 00:10:08.310
And I started driving
that to the party

00:10:08.310 --> 00:10:11.420
so I could really floss and
get everyone's attention.

00:10:11.420 --> 00:10:12.920
And they were like,
who is this kid?

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:14.966
And I was like, you
should come to my parties.

00:10:14.966 --> 00:10:16.590
And I said, we're
playing hip-hop, too.

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:19.800
And I started getting basically
all these rappers of Atlanta

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:21.660
started coming to my events.

00:10:21.660 --> 00:10:22.860
And I wasn't paying them.

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:24.901
They were coming for free
and having a good time.

00:10:24.901 --> 00:10:27.450
And the first artists I
ever worked at my parties

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:30.640
was a DJ in Atlanta
called Chris Lova

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:33.517
Lova, who had an alternate
personality named Ludacris.

00:10:33.517 --> 00:10:35.350
And he had a record
called "Throw Dem 'Bows"

00:10:35.350 --> 00:10:38.141
and that was the first
record I ever worked.

00:10:38.141 --> 00:10:39.890
And that's how I kind
of got on the scene.

00:10:39.890 --> 00:10:43.147
And then one day,
Jermaine Dupri called me.

00:10:43.147 --> 00:10:44.730
And he was-- when
you came to Atlanta,

00:10:44.730 --> 00:10:46.896
there was a big billboard
that used to say, Welcome,

00:10:46.896 --> 00:10:48.120
the Home of So So Def.

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:49.697
And he was on top of his game.

00:10:49.697 --> 00:10:51.030
A lot of people don't know this.

00:10:51.030 --> 00:10:53.490
Jermaine Dupri is the
only producer in music

00:10:53.490 --> 00:10:55.960
to have a number one on the
Billboard charts for 16 years

00:10:55.960 --> 00:10:57.185
straight.

00:10:57.185 --> 00:10:58.060
JESSE MICHELS: Crazy.

00:10:58.060 --> 00:10:59.643
SCOOTER BRAUN: More
than Quincy Jones.

00:10:59.643 --> 00:11:02.820
And Jermaine asked me
to come meet with him.

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:06.570
And Jermaine is not a tall man.

00:11:06.570 --> 00:11:10.220
So we met, and his feet were
dangling from this chair.

00:11:10.220 --> 00:11:11.970
And he was talking to
me and I was just so

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:15.440
