00:43:25.465 --> 00:43:26.923
JESSE MICHELS: I
didn't ask Ariana.

00:43:26.923 --> 00:43:27.910
Ariana.

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:29.420
SCOOTER BRAUN: Brave.

00:43:29.420 --> 00:43:30.991
JESSE MICHELS: Awesome.

00:43:30.991 --> 00:43:35.370
And it feels like right now,
you represent mostly pop,

00:43:35.370 --> 00:43:36.510
would you say?

00:43:36.510 --> 00:43:39.630
You came from a
hip-hop background.

00:43:39.630 --> 00:43:40.407
Yeah.

00:43:40.407 --> 00:43:41.490
How do you reconcile that?

00:43:41.490 --> 00:43:45.287
Do you want to do
more hip-hop stuff?

00:43:45.287 --> 00:43:47.620
SCOOTER BRAUN: I am in business
with more hip-hop people

00:43:47.620 --> 00:43:50.110
than I let know publicly.

00:43:50.110 --> 00:43:52.585
And I'm also in business
with a lot of country music

00:43:52.585 --> 00:43:53.960
that I don't talk
about publicly.

00:43:53.960 --> 00:43:57.610
Our company has a
branch of it that

00:43:57.610 --> 00:44:01.730
owns a piece of a bunch of other
companies within our business.

00:44:01.730 --> 00:44:03.550
So we own 50% of a lot
of other companies.

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:05.091
We just don't talk
about it publicly.

00:44:05.091 --> 00:44:07.150
It allows me to
touch other genres,

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:10.360
be involved with other genres.

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:12.730
And we've done EDM.

00:44:12.730 --> 00:44:15.780
We've done country.

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:17.739
But there's people that
they'll see me at shows

00:44:17.739 --> 00:44:20.279
and be like, I didn't know you
were friends with this person.

00:44:20.279 --> 00:44:22.600
And sometimes, I'm in
business with them as well.

00:44:22.600 --> 00:44:27.370
But it's funny, because
probably of any manager

00:44:27.370 --> 00:44:30.110
in music history, I've
probably put myself

00:44:30.110 --> 00:44:32.120
out there probably
the most, because I

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:33.360
thought it was a new world.

00:44:33.360 --> 00:44:35.936
And if you can create
a brand for yourself,

00:44:35.936 --> 00:44:37.310
then you can launch
other brands.

00:44:37.310 --> 00:44:38.860
And social media
was changing things.

00:44:38.860 --> 00:44:40.580
So I made a conscious
decision to do that,

00:44:40.580 --> 00:44:42.454
knowing that it would
put a target on my back

00:44:42.454 --> 00:44:44.870
and it would be something
people used to criticize me

00:44:44.870 --> 00:44:47.479
and kind of judge my
character and assume that--

00:44:47.479 --> 00:44:49.520
people that don't know
me, they might assume, oh,

00:44:49.520 --> 00:44:52.070
he's doing that because he
wants to become a public figure

00:44:52.070 --> 00:44:53.360
or be consumed by that.

00:44:53.360 --> 00:44:55.940
And the truth is, the majority
of the successes we have,

00:44:55.940 --> 00:44:58.310
we'll never speak about.

00:44:58.310 --> 00:45:02.900
And the majority of my private
life isn't very public.

00:45:02.900 --> 00:45:07.690
I choose to show my
family in certain aspects

00:45:07.690 --> 00:45:09.490
publicly only
because when I came

00:45:09.490 --> 00:45:14.920
into the industry, fast women,
fast cars was a stigma that you

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:20.110
thought of when you thought of
a successful entertainment man.

00:45:20.110 --> 00:45:23.730
And I wanted to
change that paradigm.

00:45:23.730 --> 00:45:26.080
I want people to
see me, and I want

00:45:26.080 --> 00:45:28.210
them to know you can have
success in this industry

00:45:28.210 --> 00:45:31.760
and be a good husband, a good
father, a good friend, a family

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:32.260
man.

00:45:32.260 --> 00:45:33.884
And I also think--
especially with what

00:45:33.884 --> 00:45:37.360
I'm seeing now with "Time's
Up" and the "Me Too" movement,

00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:40.990
that this movement can't
just be about women.

00:45:40.990 --> 00:45:42.730
This movement needs
to be about moving

00:45:42.730 --> 00:45:44.200
the needle on men
in the industry

00:45:44.200 --> 00:45:46.090
so they treat women better.

00:45:46.090 --> 00:45:46.921
And--

00:45:46.921 --> 00:45:48.959
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:48.959 --> 00:45:50.500
--I think the only
way you do that is

00:45:50.500 --> 00:45:53.260
you move the needle on
what a man's goal is.

00:45:53.260 --> 00:45:55.690
If you tell a young man
coming into the industry

00:45:55.690 --> 00:45:57.770
that success doesn't
look like that,

00:45:57.770 --> 00:46:00.760
that's actually
not a good result.

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:05.144
Success is being someone who's
honorable to women and someone

00:46:05.144 --> 00:46:07.060
who is honorable to their
family and honorable

00:46:07.060 --> 00:46:09.760
to their commitments of family.

00:46:09.760 --> 00:46:13.300
Then I think you're going to
see more young men not acting so

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:16.120
inappropriately and
becoming like the generation

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:17.510
that we're seeing
fall right now.

00:46:17.510 --> 00:46:20.004
And that is something I want.

00:46:20.004 --> 00:46:22.420
Because I was raised by a
strong woman, and I married one,

00:46:22.420 --> 00:46:27.190
so I don't want the next dude
coming up looking at my success

00:46:27.190 --> 00:46:29.650
and thinking, oh,
I want that car,

00:46:29.650 --> 00:46:31.750
and I want that young girl.

00:46:31.750 --> 00:46:33.680
No, that's not what it's about.

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:37.522
That's actually a very
shallow life, in my opinion.

00:46:37.522 --> 00:46:38.980
Sorry I talked
about this too long.

00:46:38.980 --> 00:46:40.896
JESSE MICHELS: Well,
you're a good role model.

00:46:40.896 --> 00:46:42.580
No, that's great.

00:46:42.580 --> 00:46:46.630
You talk about a lot of your
success going kind of unspoken

00:46:46.630 --> 00:46:50.050
and unrecognized or you kind
of keeping silent about it.

00:46:50.050 --> 00:46:53.440
Fittingly, the tech
arm of the SB Projects

00:46:53.440 --> 00:46:55.240
is named Silent Labs.

00:46:55.240 --> 00:46:57.660
Can you talk about-- we
were talking earlier--

00:46:57.660 --> 00:47:00.220
just the history of your
involvement with tech,

00:47:00.220 --> 00:47:04.077
to the extent that you
can talk about that?

00:47:04.077 --> 00:47:05.910
SCOOTER BRAUN: So the
itch came because when

00:47:05.910 --> 00:47:07.560
I was a big college
party promoter,

00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:10.980
Emory was one of the first eight
schools to launch the Facebook.

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:15.090
And I was like, what a great
way to get my parties out

00:47:15.090 --> 00:47:19.810
there without having to
hack the school database.

00:47:19.810 --> 00:47:22.980
So I got in touch
with the contact page

00:47:22.980 --> 00:47:26.850
and the master of dungeon
ceremonies, Mark Zuckerberg,

00:47:26.850 --> 00:47:28.620
whatever the hell
it said at the time.

00:47:28.620 --> 00:47:30.300
And he wrote me
back, please talk

00:47:30.300 --> 00:47:34.260
to Eduardo, who I saw was the
master of coin or something

00:47:34.260 --> 00:47:34.920
like that.

00:47:34.920 --> 00:47:37.950
And Eduardo and I,
for about four months,

00:47:37.950 --> 00:47:44.272
negotiated 10% of
Facebook for $100,000.

00:47:44.272 --> 00:47:45.230
I still have the email.

00:47:45.230 --> 00:47:47.480
Dear Scooter, Mark
wants to launch

00:47:47.480 --> 00:47:49.106
32 more schools in two weeks.

00:47:49.106 --> 00:47:50.480
So unfortunately
at this time, he

00:47:50.480 --> 00:47:52.847
refuses to take any
outside investment.

00:47:52.847 --> 00:47:54.680
Let me know if you're
coming to Boston so we

00:47:54.680 --> 00:47:57.570
can catch up and see if there's
other stuff we can do together.

00:47:57.570 --> 00:48:01.952
Now, I joke around in my head
that I know I'm a closer.

00:48:01.952 --> 00:48:03.410
And if I would have
gone to Boston,

00:48:03.410 --> 00:48:04.490
I probably would have
closed that deal.

00:48:04.490 --> 00:48:06.920
But remember that high school
sweetheart I told you about?

00:48:06.920 --> 00:48:09.320
Well, she ripped my heart out.

00:48:09.320 --> 00:48:12.290
And she went to BC.

00:48:12.290 --> 00:48:14.480
So the idea of going to
Boston and running into her

00:48:14.480 --> 00:48:15.847
was not happening.

00:48:15.847 --> 00:48:17.930
So I was like, aw, man,
screw this Facebook thing.

00:48:17.930 --> 00:48:19.940
I'll have to find another
way to promote my parties.

00:48:19.940 --> 00:48:21.800
And a year later, it
was like, Peter Thiel

00:48:21.800 --> 00:48:23.716
invests a million dollars
for 10% of Facebook.

00:48:23.716 --> 00:48:26.550
And I was like, I could
have made a million dollars.

00:48:26.550 --> 00:48:28.425
JESSE MICHELS: That's
an unprofitable breakup

00:48:28.425 --> 00:48:28.760
right there.

00:48:28.760 --> 00:48:29.360
SCOOTER BRAUN: Yeah.

00:48:29.360 --> 00:48:30.320
But I didn't know
what it was going

00:48:30.320 --> 00:48:31.569
to be so I can't claim credit.

00:48:31.569 --> 00:48:35.030
But when it continued becoming
this giant conglomerate,

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:37.940
it made me say, well
there was something there.

00:48:37.940 --> 00:48:40.580
And it actually made me start
investing in tech very, very

00:48:40.580 --> 00:48:43.576
early before the
music industry in LA

00:48:43.576 --> 00:48:45.200
wanted to start going
up to the Valley.

00:48:45.200 --> 00:48:47.660
I started going up and
not really telling anybody

00:48:47.660 --> 00:48:51.090
because I didn't want
anyone else going up.

00:48:51.090 --> 00:48:53.750
So I was able to get in
early in a lot of really

00:48:53.750 --> 00:48:55.180
amazing companies.

00:48:55.180 --> 00:48:56.930
And they were personal
investments for me.

00:48:56.930 --> 00:49:00.560
And then we had our incubator
if I wanted the company

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:02.840
to invest as well.

00:49:02.840 --> 00:49:04.630
But I was able to--

00:49:04.630 --> 00:49:06.740
I went up and I was meeting
with another company,

00:49:06.740 --> 00:49:08.180
and they ordered me an Uber.

00:49:08.180 --> 00:49:09.680
And I'm like, what
the hell is this?

00:49:09.680 --> 00:49:11.120
They're like, it's a new
thing here in San Francisco.

00:49:11.120 --> 00:49:12.480
It's really cool.

00:49:12.480 --> 00:49:15.020
And then a friend of mine
said, I met this guy, Travis.

00:49:15.020 --> 00:49:18.110
And I have this great picture
of Travis in my living room

00:49:18.110 --> 00:49:21.710
here in LA pitching me
about Uber coming to LA.

00:49:21.710 --> 00:49:23.210
And I was already
an investor when

00:49:23.210 --> 00:49:26.150
it was just in San Francisco.

00:49:26.150 --> 00:49:30.290
And seeing that whole thing,
and then his competitor

00:49:30.290 --> 00:49:35.050
came up, which I got
into also, which made him

00:49:35.050 --> 00:49:36.395
mad at me for a little while.

00:49:36.395 --> 00:49:38.020
But John Zimmer went
to my high school.

00:49:38.020 --> 00:49:39.811
John Zimmer was the
same age as my brother.

00:49:39.811 --> 00:49:42.100
He played soccer
with my brother.

00:49:42.100 --> 00:49:44.769
When that thing happened,
at first it was Zimride

00:49:44.769 --> 00:49:46.810
and I basically passed
because I was an Uber guy.

00:49:46.810 --> 00:49:49.820
But later on, I had
some frustrations

00:49:49.820 --> 00:49:52.030
and I decided, John, OK.

00:49:52.030 --> 00:49:54.130
You know, let's go do this too.

00:49:54.130 --> 00:49:58.450
And I was on a 30 under 30 list
in Billboard when I was 27.

00:49:58.450 --> 00:50:00.880
There was a 24-year-old
kid on the list.

00:50:00.880 --> 00:50:02.067
And I called up Billboard.

00:50:02.067 --> 00:50:03.650
Bill Werde was the
editor, and I said,

00:50:03.650 --> 00:50:05.710
can I have the name and
number of every single person

00:50:05.710 --> 00:50:06.209
on the list?

00:50:06.209 --> 00:50:09.610
Because I feel like my
peers are the people

00:50:09.610 --> 00:50:11.980
that I want to grow with,
not somebody I aspire to be.

00:50:11.980 --> 00:50:12.790
We're going to come up together.

00:50:12.790 --> 00:50:14.720
Because whenever you meet
someone powerful, they say,

00:50:14.720 --> 00:50:15.430
oh, of course I know them.

00:50:15.430 --> 00:50:16.055
I'll call them.

00:50:16.055 --> 00:50:17.505
We've known each other 30 years.

00:50:17.505 --> 00:50:19.630
And you realize that the
people sitting next to you

00:50:19.630 --> 00:50:21.190
when you're working your
way up are the people

00:50:21.190 --> 00:50:23.482
that you actually are going
to need when you get there.

00:50:23.482 --> 00:50:25.523
So I called everyone on
the list, and one of them

00:50:25.523 --> 00:50:27.310
was a young guy from
Sweden with a startup

00:50:27.310 --> 00:50:28.870
that was just in Sweden.

00:50:28.870 --> 00:50:32.046
We became friends,
and he let me invest

00:50:32.046 --> 00:50:33.295
in his startup called Spotify.

00:50:36.430 --> 00:50:40.180
And along the way,
different friends

00:50:40.180 --> 00:50:41.630
got me into different companies.

00:50:41.630 --> 00:50:45.419
And it worked out.

00:50:45.419 --> 00:50:46.960
JESSE MICHELS: You
make it seem easy,

00:50:46.960 --> 00:50:48.584
like you were like
accidentally friends

00:50:48.584 --> 00:50:49.820
with all-- that's crazy.

00:50:49.820 --> 00:50:50.903
SCOOTER BRAUN: No, listen.

00:50:50.903 --> 00:50:52.770
I just think--

00:50:52.770 --> 00:50:55.380
I don't really think I'm
that good at this stuff.

00:50:55.380 --> 00:50:58.431
I really think I'm really lucky.

00:50:58.431 --> 00:51:00.180
When I was a kid and
I didn't do homework,

00:51:00.180 --> 00:51:02.105
there'd be like
a freak snow day.

00:51:02.105 --> 00:51:03.480
Because I've got
a lot of friends

00:51:03.480 --> 00:51:05.280
who work really, really
hard, and they just

00:51:05.280 --> 00:51:06.960
can't catch a break.

00:51:06.960 --> 00:51:10.440
And I'm the dude who goes on the
internet in the middle of night

00:51:10.440 --> 00:51:12.720
and finds Justin, or
my friend sends me

00:51:12.720 --> 00:51:14.762
a funny video of an
overweight Asian dude dancing

00:51:14.762 --> 00:51:16.469
and I'm like, oh, it's
like the Macarena.

00:51:16.469 --> 00:51:17.400
I'll sign that.

00:51:17.400 --> 00:51:18.870
And it's Gangnam Style.

00:51:18.870 --> 00:51:24.060
And the things that have
happened to me in my career,

00:51:24.060 --> 00:51:25.682
it just doesn't
really make sense.

00:51:25.682 --> 00:51:27.140
So I don't really
think it's on me.

00:51:27.140 --> 00:51:29.940
I think somebody-- I'm going to
get real spiritual on you guys,

00:51:29.940 --> 00:51:31.398
but I actually
really believe this,

00:51:31.398 --> 00:51:33.470
because when you cry
to your dad at 25

00:51:33.470 --> 00:51:36.850
and then you wake up 11
years later next to who

00:51:36.850 --> 00:51:40.960
I get to wake up with, with
my two kids and my life,

00:51:40.960 --> 00:51:44.640
you can't just sit there and
be like, OK, this is normal,

00:51:44.640 --> 00:51:45.840
because it's not.

00:51:45.840 --> 00:51:48.532
So I believe that
you get blessings

00:51:48.532 --> 00:51:49.740
to give them to other people.

00:51:49.740 --> 00:51:52.080
Otherwise you stop getting them.

00:51:52.080 --> 00:51:54.300
That's actually my
personal belief.

00:51:54.300 --> 00:51:57.330
And I believe as long as
we keep doing philanthropy,

00:51:57.330 --> 00:52:00.600
as long as we keep giving back,
as long as we wake up every day

00:52:00.600 --> 00:52:02.670
and find a way to make
sure somebody else

00:52:02.670 --> 00:52:04.950
gets an opportunity,
then somebody upstairs

00:52:04.950 --> 00:52:07.240
keeps opening the door
for more opportunities.

00:52:07.240 --> 00:52:09.310
And that's just my
personal belief.

00:52:09.310 --> 00:52:12.210
And there are
really shitty people

00:52:12.210 --> 00:52:14.620
who get to win along the way.

00:52:14.620 --> 00:52:18.060
I'm not interested in
paying attention to them.

00:52:18.060 --> 00:52:19.424
We've just got to do what we do.

00:52:19.424 --> 00:52:20.757
JESSE MICHELS: That's beautiful.

