AUDIENCE: Oh, you're
going to toss it.

00:53:42.780 --> 00:53:44.090
That's part of the fun.

00:53:44.090 --> 00:53:45.370
JESSE MICHELS: And feel
free to pass to the next--

00:53:45.370 --> 00:53:45.770
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:53:45.770 --> 00:53:46.330
JESSE MICHELS: Cool.

00:53:46.330 --> 00:53:48.746
AUDIENCE: Diana [INAUDIBLE],,
thanks for being here today.

00:53:48.746 --> 00:53:50.570
You are an amazing storyteller.

00:53:50.570 --> 00:53:52.980
I've learned so much just
from listening to you.

00:53:52.980 --> 00:53:57.330
You've talked a lot about using
technology like social media

00:53:57.330 --> 00:54:00.210
to discover new music
and new artists.

00:54:00.210 --> 00:54:04.290
Thoughts on super new technology
that could potentially

00:54:04.290 --> 00:54:05.820
be used to discover new music?

00:54:05.820 --> 00:54:08.510
Like robots, self-driving
cars, drones?

00:54:08.510 --> 00:54:11.280
And to give some context, I
work at Google X. I'm just--

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:12.363
SCOOTER BRAUN: Blockchain.

00:54:12.363 --> 00:54:13.300
No, I'm kidding.

00:54:13.300 --> 00:54:14.174
AUDIENCE: Blockchain.

00:54:14.174 --> 00:54:15.465
Yeah, I think that will work.

00:54:19.110 --> 00:54:21.510
SCOOTER BRAUN: Technology
has actually always shaped

00:54:21.510 --> 00:54:23.330
how we see the music industry.

00:54:23.330 --> 00:54:28.532
So before Tesla really created
what we know as radio today,

00:54:28.532 --> 00:54:30.240
there was no music
industry because there

00:54:30.240 --> 00:54:31.407
wasn't a way to distribute.

00:54:31.407 --> 00:54:33.990
So technology actually was the
creation of the music industry.

00:54:33.990 --> 00:54:39.660
And then if you look at
whether it be vinyl and then

00:54:39.660 --> 00:54:44.160
the adaption to 8-track and
then CDs and cassettes and all

00:54:44.160 --> 00:54:47.850
these different things and then
going to MP3 and now streaming,

00:54:47.850 --> 00:54:50.310
technology has
always built, lifted,

00:54:50.310 --> 00:54:52.380
and saved the music industry.

00:54:52.380 --> 00:54:54.810
I have no idea what
it's going to be next.

00:54:54.810 --> 00:54:56.520
I know that I think
we're actually

00:54:56.520 --> 00:54:58.500
in the infant
stage of streaming.

00:54:58.500 --> 00:55:00.583
Because if you actually
look at it and we're like,

00:55:00.583 --> 00:55:03.630
oh my god, this person
sold 5 million albums.

00:55:03.630 --> 00:55:05.049
That's mind blowing.

00:55:05.049 --> 00:55:06.840
But the amount of people
on the planet that

00:55:06.840 --> 00:55:08.923
listen to music, that
actually isn't mind blowing.

00:55:08.923 --> 00:55:11.730
We've never created
a way where, when

00:55:11.730 --> 00:55:14.520
there's such a great separation
of wealth in this world,

00:55:14.520 --> 00:55:16.980
to be able to distribute music
properly amongst all people.

00:55:16.980 --> 00:55:20.810
And now we have streaming,
which is changing that.

00:55:20.810 --> 00:55:24.080
So I don't really know,
necessarily, what's next.

00:55:24.080 --> 00:55:26.330
I know I think
we're in round one.

00:55:26.330 --> 00:55:28.251
I mean, I think
it's $8.6 billion

00:55:28.251 --> 00:55:30.500
that streaming is now creating
for the industry, which

00:55:30.500 --> 00:55:33.890
has brought it back up to where
it was and a little bit above.

00:55:33.890 --> 00:55:35.990
I think we're in,
literally, the first inning

00:55:35.990 --> 00:55:38.000
of a nine-inning
game of streaming.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:40.160
I think it's going to
take the value of music

00:55:40.160 --> 00:55:42.920
up in a way we
haven't seen before.

00:55:42.920 --> 00:55:48.004
And then I think as far AI, that
is the most interesting part

00:55:48.004 --> 00:55:49.670
for me, because that's
how we're getting

00:55:49.670 --> 00:55:51.544
a lot of this playlisting
and everything else

00:55:51.544 --> 00:55:52.850
that's becoming so influential.

00:55:52.850 --> 00:55:58.260
But I still think it's
missing the human touch.

00:55:58.260 --> 00:56:02.250
Because AI can kind of
identify what songs go together

00:56:02.250 --> 00:56:04.740
or how we put stuff
together, but a human touch

00:56:04.740 --> 00:56:09.730
can identify a human's
interaction with music

00:56:09.730 --> 00:56:11.380
in a timeline of life.

00:56:11.380 --> 00:56:15.860
Because if I say to
you, tell me what

00:56:15.860 --> 00:56:18.590
you were doing when
you were 11 years old,

00:56:18.590 --> 00:56:19.860
you're probably not going to--

00:56:19.860 --> 00:56:21.790
maybe something influential
happened when you were 11.

00:56:21.790 --> 00:56:23.873
But a lot of people are
like, I'm not really sure.

00:56:23.873 --> 00:56:26.030
But if I play you a really
big song from that year,

00:56:26.030 --> 00:56:27.405
it's going to take
you right back

00:56:27.405 --> 00:56:28.940
to when you were 11 years old.

00:56:28.940 --> 00:56:32.600
And there's something
special that AI can't

00:56:32.600 --> 00:56:35.450
do about identifying that.

00:56:35.450 --> 00:56:39.660
But also there's so many
people we're going to need AI.

00:56:39.660 --> 00:56:41.930
So I'm interested to
see what someone like

00:56:41.930 --> 00:56:43.640
yourself comes up with next.

00:56:43.640 --> 00:56:45.860
And hopefully, by
the time you do,

00:56:45.860 --> 00:56:47.360
I will be out of
the music industry.

00:56:47.360 --> 00:56:48.230
No, I'm kidding.

00:56:48.230 --> 00:56:49.177
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:49.177 --> 00:56:50.010
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:56:52.900 --> 00:56:54.300
SCOOTER BRAUN: Good throw.

00:56:54.300 --> 00:56:58.940
AUDIENCE: So, Scooter, what
are your thoughts on blockchain

00:56:58.940 --> 00:56:59.630
technology?

00:57:04.800 --> 00:57:07.090
SCOOTER BRAUN: My thoughts
are blockchain technology

00:57:07.090 --> 00:57:09.750
is amazing, and it's going
to be innovative in 100

00:57:09.750 --> 00:57:11.850
different industries.

00:57:11.850 --> 00:57:16.210
But coins aren't needed
in every single industry.

00:57:16.210 --> 00:57:18.360
So I think having
a coin associated

00:57:18.360 --> 00:57:20.970
to every piece of
blockchain technology

00:57:20.970 --> 00:57:24.900
is why 99% of the
coins will disappear.

00:57:24.900 --> 00:57:26.961
And the ones that make
sense for the technology

00:57:26.961 --> 00:57:29.460
that they're associated with
and make sense for the industry

00:57:29.460 --> 00:57:31.320
that they're going
into will survive.

00:57:31.320 --> 00:57:35.340
And those coins will be
the Amazon of this bubble.

00:57:35.340 --> 00:57:38.940
But I think that there's
a very big difference

00:57:38.940 --> 00:57:42.000
between blockchain technology
and cryptocurrency,

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:43.120
in my opinion.

00:57:43.120 --> 00:57:48.160
And I think that the actual
use of blockchain technology--

00:57:48.160 --> 00:57:50.160
listen, if they can break
blockchain technology,

00:57:50.160 --> 00:57:50.790
we're all screwed.

00:57:50.790 --> 00:57:52.456
Because that means
that people can break

00:57:52.456 --> 00:57:54.900
our entire financial system.

00:57:54.900 --> 00:57:58.260
But I think it's going to
make all of our systems

00:57:58.260 --> 00:58:00.559
more efficient.

00:58:00.559 --> 00:58:02.850
But I think that people should
start educating themself

00:58:02.850 --> 00:58:05.730
on the difference between
crypto and what blockchain

00:58:05.730 --> 00:58:08.825
is, and actually
understand that it's way

00:58:08.825 --> 00:58:10.950
too easy to make coins,
and that's why most of them

00:58:10.950 --> 00:58:11.995
should disappear.

00:58:11.995 --> 00:58:14.970
But until then, I'm going to
have as much fun as you are.

00:58:18.149 --> 00:58:20.190
JESSE MICHELS: [INAUDIBLE]
right in front of you.

00:58:20.190 --> 00:58:21.222
Oh, right there.

00:58:21.222 --> 00:58:22.930
AUDIENCE: Scooter,
this has been awesome.

00:58:22.930 --> 00:58:24.410
Thanks for coming.

00:58:24.410 --> 00:58:26.420
You're a tremendously
successful entrepreneur

00:58:26.420 --> 00:58:30.710
across a range of industries--
tech, non-profits, music,

00:58:30.710 --> 00:58:31.619
media.

00:58:31.619 --> 00:58:33.410
What excites you the
most in your business?

00:58:38.600 --> 00:58:41.720
SCOOTER BRAUN: I'm really
cheesy now that I'm a dad--

00:58:41.720 --> 00:58:43.710
bed time.

00:58:43.710 --> 00:58:44.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:44.680 --> 00:58:50.540
I mean honestly, I get
excited by challenges,

00:58:50.540 --> 00:58:52.850
and I get excited by insults.

00:58:52.850 --> 00:58:56.510
So when everyone is like,
oh, you've done so well,

00:58:56.510 --> 00:58:59.270
I get really bored, because
I don't know where to go.

00:58:59.270 --> 00:59:00.830
Insults have
usually led me where

00:59:00.830 --> 00:59:03.860
to go because doing
the unreasonable thing

00:59:03.860 --> 00:59:06.516
has always led to
the great thing.

00:59:06.516 --> 00:59:08.390
Doing what everyone
expects-- the status quo,

00:59:08.390 --> 00:59:10.681
the reasonable-- doesn't lead
to any kind of greatness,

00:59:10.681 --> 00:59:12.260
doesn't lead to a good story.

00:59:12.260 --> 00:59:15.440
And I always said I wanted to be
my own story instead of reading

00:59:15.440 --> 00:59:18.530
everyone else's.

00:59:18.530 --> 00:59:22.118
But what gets me
excited at this point--

00:59:22.118 --> 00:59:24.650
who here is a parent?

00:59:24.650 --> 00:59:26.002
OK.

00:59:26.002 --> 00:59:28.460
So the people that raised their
hand are going to get this.

00:59:28.460 --> 00:59:30.920
My kid, my 3-year-old,
woke me up this morning,

00:59:30.920 --> 00:59:36.790
slapped me in my forehead,
and said, Daddy, I love you.

00:59:36.790 --> 00:59:38.670
So much better than a Grammy.

00:59:38.670 --> 00:59:42.350
So much better than,
you know, an IPO.

00:59:42.350 --> 00:59:44.590
There's no real describing it.

00:59:44.590 --> 00:59:46.150
Because you do all
this stuff and you

00:59:46.150 --> 00:59:46.870
don't really understand.

00:59:46.870 --> 00:59:48.160
You're like, what am I here for?

00:59:48.160 --> 00:59:49.118
And then you have kids.

00:59:49.118 --> 00:59:52.205
And then you understand what
you actually are here for.

00:59:52.205 --> 00:59:54.580
You have a purpose, when you
have children, that you just

00:59:54.580 --> 00:59:55.880
didn't have before.

00:59:55.880 --> 00:59:57.534
And there's no good
time to have kids,

00:59:57.534 --> 00:59:59.200
because you're always
planning your life

00:59:59.200 --> 01:00:00.310
and seeing it through
your own eyes.

01:00:00.310 --> 01:00:01.960
And then when they finally
show up, you're like,

01:00:01.960 --> 01:00:02.890
I don't really
understand what life

01:00:02.890 --> 01:00:04.560
would have been without you.

01:00:04.560 --> 01:00:05.620
Yeah, I know I sucked.

01:00:05.620 --> 01:00:07.110
You guys are leaving?

01:00:07.110 --> 01:00:08.470
You guys want to leave?

01:00:08.470 --> 01:00:09.280
Yeah, I know.

01:00:09.280 --> 01:00:11.665
I saw Dave Chapelle do this
one time at The Comedy Store.

01:00:11.665 --> 01:00:13.790
He did, like, a [INAUDIBLE]
when people walked out.

01:00:13.790 --> 01:00:14.550
And he did this.

01:00:14.550 --> 01:00:17.008
Everyone give him a round of
applause because they hate me.

01:00:17.008 --> 01:00:18.958
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:22.270 --> 01:00:23.110
I like [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:23.110 --> 01:00:26.980
What makes me excited
is either the first time

01:00:26.980 --> 01:00:30.070
I do something, being with my
family, experience like that,

01:00:30.070 --> 01:00:33.050
or when someone I
work with has a first.

01:00:33.050 --> 01:00:35.860
Like, the first time I saw
this guy, Mike George, who

01:00:35.860 --> 01:00:39.424
works for me, receive his first
platinum plaque in our company,

01:00:39.424 --> 01:00:40.840
I had, at that
point in my career,

01:00:40.840 --> 01:00:42.580
received a lot of
platinum plaques.

01:00:42.580 --> 01:00:45.160
They're in the garage.

01:00:45.160 --> 01:00:48.370
Seeing him have the
joy of that first time

01:00:48.370 --> 01:00:51.320
reminded me of what that felt
like, and that gives me joy.

01:00:51.320 --> 01:00:53.890
So I'm kind of at
a point now where

01:00:53.890 --> 01:00:57.030
I feel like my life
is kind of absurd,

01:00:57.030 --> 01:01:00.090
and I have everything I've
ever needed and a lot more.

01:01:00.090 --> 01:01:01.590
And I only got there
because I stood

01:01:01.590 --> 01:01:03.660
on the shoulders of all these
people that believed in me.

01:01:03.660 --> 01:01:05.730
So now it's my turn to
kind of work for them

01:01:05.730 --> 01:01:08.030
and make sure I pull
them up to where I'm at.

01:01:08.030 --> 01:01:08.780
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

01:01:08.780 --> 01:01:09.280
Thanks.

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:14.060
AUDIENCE: So what
was your response

01:01:14.060 --> 01:01:19.650
when Kanye West showed kind
of support for Donald Trump?

01:01:19.650 --> 01:01:21.860
SCOOTER BRAUN: I disagreed.

01:01:21.860 --> 01:01:25.850
I mean, it's-- here's the thing.

01:01:25.850 --> 01:01:27.682
Living in Los
Angeles, I'm really

01:01:27.682 --> 01:01:29.390
grateful that I lived
in Atlanta, Georgia

01:01:29.390 --> 01:01:32.600
until six years ago.

01:01:32.600 --> 01:01:34.554
Living in Los Angeles
and New York is amazing.

01:01:34.554 --> 01:01:35.970
And living in the
state's amazing,

01:01:35.970 --> 01:01:39.980
because it's probably the most
forward state in the nation.

01:01:39.980 --> 01:01:42.110
But we're not without
fault. The largest

01:01:42.110 --> 01:01:44.900
separation of wealth in the
country is in this state.

01:01:44.900 --> 01:01:49.670
And people acted like they lost
their damn minds when he won.

01:01:49.670 --> 01:01:51.800
And to me, when he won,
I didn't freak out.

01:01:51.800 --> 01:01:53.289
Because that's the process.

01:01:53.289 --> 01:01:54.830
Someone needs to
win, and then you're

01:01:54.830 --> 01:01:56.661
supposed to heal
and come together.

01:01:56.661 --> 01:01:58.160
A lot of things
that he's done since

01:01:58.160 --> 01:02:00.740
have disappointed me to
a place that I'm not OK.

01:02:00.740 --> 01:02:02.240
But I was going to
give him a chance

01:02:02.240 --> 01:02:05.370
in the beginning, because
I think that's the process.

01:02:05.370 --> 01:02:07.400
And if you don't, then
you're a hypocrite.

01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:10.497
Because if Hillary would
have won and they said, oh,

01:02:10.497 --> 01:02:12.080
we don't want to
support her, we would

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:15.016
have been yelling at them.

01:02:15.016 --> 01:02:16.640
So when he felt that
way, I said, look,

01:02:16.640 --> 01:02:17.780
that's your opinion.

01:02:17.780 --> 01:02:19.870
But I also felt like he
was feeling that way when

01:02:19.870 --> 01:02:23.990
at a point where he was sick.

01:02:23.990 --> 01:02:26.159
And I felt like there
were people around him--

01:02:26.159 --> 01:02:27.200
it was very frustrating--

01:02:27.200 --> 01:02:29.952
I thought were taking advantage
of a time where-- like,

01:02:29.952 --> 01:02:31.910
if you saw Quincy Jones'
most recent interview,

01:02:31.910 --> 01:02:32.990
nobody should have
let that person

01:02:32.990 --> 01:02:34.031
in the house at the time.

01:02:34.031 --> 01:02:36.320
Like, sometimes people
need to be given privacy.

01:02:36.320 --> 01:02:37.820
Just because they're
public figures,

01:02:37.820 --> 01:02:41.330
they need to be given
a moment to process.

01:02:41.330 --> 01:02:44.210
But I know his heart.

01:02:44.210 --> 01:02:46.270
And I know that
he's a human being

01:02:46.270 --> 01:02:47.990
that I don't always agree with.

01:02:47.990 --> 01:02:48.870
But I respect him.

01:02:48.870 --> 01:02:51.140
And he said what
he wanted to say.

01:02:51.140 --> 01:02:53.262
And I'm allowed to
have my own opinion.

01:02:53.262 --> 01:02:55.220
You know, just because
I manage someone doesn't

01:02:55.220 --> 01:02:56.511
mean I need to agree with them.

01:02:56.511 --> 01:02:59.540
Me and Vic Mensa, who I
manage, had a big disagreement

01:02:59.540 --> 01:03:00.304
recently.

01:03:00.304 --> 01:03:02.720
And I was proud that he put
up on his Instagram-- he said,

01:03:02.720 --> 01:03:05.240
I know Scooter Braun
vehemently disagreed with me,

01:03:05.240 --> 01:03:06.140
and he's my manager.

01:03:06.140 --> 01:03:08.900
But I appreciate him at
least having a conversation.

01:03:08.900 --> 01:03:11.204
I think we've messed
up in this country.

01:03:11.204 --> 01:03:12.620
And really around
the world, we've

01:03:12.620 --> 01:03:14.580
forgotten how to
speak to each other.

01:03:14.580 --> 01:03:15.590
And we're forgetting
the same people

01:03:15.590 --> 01:03:17.548
who were yelling at other
people we're claiming

01:03:17.548 --> 01:03:18.720
that we're supposed to help.

01:03:18.720 --> 01:03:20.690
And I think we need to
start having conversations

01:03:20.690 --> 01:03:21.564
out of respect again.

01:03:21.564 --> 01:03:24.804
Otherwise, nothing
is going to change.

01:03:24.804 --> 01:03:25.660
AUDIENCE: Cool.

01:03:25.660 --> 01:03:26.320
SCOOTER BRAUN:
You've got to throw

01:03:26.320 --> 01:03:27.820
it all the way over there.

01:03:27.820 --> 01:03:31.240
You have to throw it.

01:03:31.240 --> 01:03:32.830
Oh, good catch.

01:03:32.830 --> 01:03:36.340
I thought she was going
a U. She went deep.

01:03:36.340 --> 01:03:38.749
She's got a Kirk Cousins arm.

01:03:38.749 --> 01:03:41.290
AUDIENCE: So first of all, I
was a college student in Atlanta

01:03:41.290 --> 01:03:43.051
from 2002 to 2006.

01:03:43.051 --> 01:03:44.800
So I probably went to
some of your parties

01:03:44.800 --> 01:03:46.600
and didn't even know it.

01:03:46.600 --> 01:03:49.434
But you mentioned about
how when you have success,

01:03:49.434 --> 01:03:51.100
you get bored, and
you're kind of always

01:03:51.100 --> 01:03:52.433
looking for that next challenge.

01:03:52.433 --> 01:03:54.460
So is there something
on the horizon for you

01:03:54.460 --> 01:03:58.000
that you feel like is some
sort of moonshot thing

01:03:58.000 --> 01:03:59.500
that you think
you'll go after next?

01:03:59.500 --> 01:04:01.510
Or is it just going
to be bringing up

01:04:01.510 --> 01:04:04.330
those people behind you
and all of those things?

01:04:04.330 --> 01:04:06.080
SCOOTER BRAUN: I think
it's a combination.

01:04:06.080 --> 01:04:09.080
If I want to bring them up,
then I've got to keep going.

01:04:09.080 --> 01:04:14.290
So the way I look at it,
here's the challenge.

01:04:14.290 --> 01:04:15.520
I'm 36 years old.

01:04:15.520 --> 01:04:17.680
He's like, you've
got a cool story.

01:04:17.680 --> 01:04:19.940
If this is the end of
my story, then I failed.

01:04:19.940 --> 01:04:21.200
Because I'm 36.

01:04:21.200 --> 01:04:24.610
The average entrepreneur
hits their stride at 39.

01:04:24.610 --> 01:04:28.540
So to me, I'm just
getting started.

01:04:28.540 --> 01:04:30.699
So I don't know,
necessarily, what it is next,

01:04:30.699 --> 01:04:32.990
and I don't like talking
about stuff before it happens.

01:04:32.990 --> 01:04:34.790
So there's things
we're working on.

01:04:34.790 --> 01:04:37.570
But I also know part of my story
is going to include failure.

01:04:37.570 --> 01:04:40.060
Because the last decade of my
life has had so much success

01:04:40.060 --> 01:04:43.030
that statistically-- if I'm
really not being a moron

01:04:43.030 --> 01:04:45.490
and paying attention
to a little data--

01:04:45.490 --> 01:04:48.100
statistically, I should
have some serious failure

01:04:48.100 --> 01:04:49.420
on the horizon.

01:04:49.420 --> 01:04:51.760
You know, the Wall Street
goes up, it goes down.

01:04:51.760 --> 01:04:53.343
There's always got
to be a correction.

01:04:53.343 --> 01:04:55.840
So what I'm excited
about is regardless

01:04:55.840 --> 01:04:58.090
of what that correction is,
it's not going to stop me.

01:04:58.090 --> 01:05:00.700
It's just going
to be a pit stop.

01:05:00.700 --> 01:05:05.180
Because now, where the
universe messed up is

01:05:05.180 --> 01:05:06.830
they gave me too much.

01:05:06.830 --> 01:05:10.040
Now that I got my wife and kids,
I'm playing with house money.

01:05:10.040 --> 01:05:12.470
So you can't really take
anything away from me.

01:05:12.470 --> 01:05:15.590
If I lose some money, or
like lose some popular--

01:05:15.590 --> 01:05:17.960
you know, if I drop the
ball and some naysayers who

01:05:17.960 --> 01:05:20.540
wanted to see me fail are
all like, I told you so,

01:05:20.540 --> 01:05:22.915
they're going to be super
disappointed when they find out

01:05:22.915 --> 01:05:24.142
I'm not that upset.

01:05:24.142 --> 01:05:26.600
But I'm just going to keep
going and see where it takes me.

01:05:26.600 --> 01:05:30.030
And whatever comes
next, I'm ready for it.

01:05:30.030 --> 01:05:31.340
And I get bored.

01:05:31.340 --> 01:05:34.230
But I also, I'm a workaholic.

01:05:34.230 --> 01:05:36.290
I can't really shut it off.

01:05:36.290 --> 01:05:38.990
The hardest challenge for
me is work/life balance.

01:05:38.990 --> 01:05:41.376
I'm constantly getting better.

01:05:41.376 --> 01:05:43.250
But my wife-- she was
the one who said to me.

01:05:43.250 --> 01:05:45.833
She goes, there's a difference
between being present and being

01:05:45.833 --> 01:05:47.060
present.

01:05:47.060 --> 01:05:50.900
And that's the thing I'm
working on the most at home,

01:05:50.900 --> 01:05:54.400
putting the phone down
and being present.

01:05:54.400 --> 01:05:55.300
AUDIENCE: Good luck.

01:05:55.300 --> 01:05:56.480
SCOOTER BRAUN: Thanks.

01:05:56.480 --> 01:05:59.862
I hope you enjoyed the
party back in the day.

01:05:59.862 --> 01:06:00.570
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

01:06:00.570 --> 01:06:02.500
This has been awesome.

01:06:02.500 --> 01:06:03.970
I'm curious.

01:06:03.970 --> 01:06:07.480
Do you think you could have been
as successful had you pursued

01:06:07.480 --> 01:06:08.836
a completely different path?

01:06:08.836 --> 01:06:10.210
Like, how much of
your success is

01:06:10.210 --> 01:06:12.820
attributable to your
passion for music

01:06:12.820 --> 01:06:17.590
and your craft, as opposed
to just your inherent drive?

01:06:17.590 --> 01:06:19.090
SCOOTER BRAUN: I
mean, I don't know.

01:06:19.090 --> 01:06:20.770
I know that I didn't go
into life being like,

01:06:20.770 --> 01:06:21.894
you know what I want to do?

01:06:21.894 --> 01:06:23.380
Music.

01:06:23.380 --> 01:06:24.905
I just wanted to
be an entrepreneur.

01:06:24.905 --> 01:06:27.280
And that's the way I've always
kind of considered myself.

01:06:27.280 --> 01:06:28.821
And I read a book
about David Geffen,

01:06:28.821 --> 01:06:31.060
where he said music
was the fastest way in.

01:06:31.060 --> 01:06:32.890
Because music takes a night.

01:06:32.890 --> 01:06:34.930
And movies and TV and
entertainment take years.

01:06:34.930 --> 01:06:36.540
But the one song can change
your life in a night.

01:06:36.540 --> 01:06:37.850
I was like, I'm in Atlanta.

01:06:37.850 --> 01:06:38.350
Let's go.

01:06:40.940 --> 01:06:44.652
But I don't know what
my life would have been.

01:06:44.652 --> 01:06:46.360
I think there's so
many points in my life

01:06:46.360 --> 01:06:47.505
I look back and
think, if I would

01:06:47.505 --> 01:06:49.000
have turned that way
instead of that way, what

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:49.834
would have happened?

01:06:49.834 --> 01:06:52.208
You know, if I would've stayed
in that relationship, what

01:06:52.208 --> 01:06:53.130
would have happened?

01:06:53.130 --> 01:06:55.380
You know, there's so many
different ways I look at it.

01:06:55.380 --> 01:06:57.760
All I know is I thank
God every day I wake up,

01:06:57.760 --> 01:06:59.440
and this is where I ended up.

01:06:59.440 --> 01:07:02.821
Because I'm 36 years old,
and whenever I get depressed,

01:07:02.821 --> 01:07:04.570
the one thing I remind
myself of is, like,

01:07:04.570 --> 01:07:08.070
if you put my life against
any 36-year-old on the planet,

01:07:08.070 --> 01:07:10.230
I'm going to take my life.

01:07:10.230 --> 01:07:11.410
I'm going to choose this.

01:07:11.410 --> 01:07:13.970
This is good stuff for 36.

01:07:13.970 --> 01:07:15.010
I'm working with this.

01:07:15.010 --> 01:07:16.210
This is fine by me.

01:07:16.210 --> 01:07:17.200
Except for the Jets.

01:07:17.200 --> 01:07:18.272
We never win.

01:07:18.272 --> 01:07:19.780
[LAUGHTER]

01:07:19.780 --> 01:07:22.390
I see you with the
Steelers shirt.

01:07:22.390 --> 01:07:22.890
Sorry.

01:07:26.480 --> 01:07:27.480
AUDIENCE: This is great.

01:07:27.480 --> 01:07:29.140
And I actually listen to
you on [INAUDIBLE] as well.

01:07:29.140 --> 01:07:30.887
So I'm one of your
three basketball fans.

01:07:30.887 --> 01:07:31.720
SCOOTER BRAUN: Nice.

01:07:31.720 --> 01:07:32.160
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:07:32.160 --> 01:07:33.280
SCOOTER BRAUN: That
was fun with Bill.

01:07:33.280 --> 01:07:33.690
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:07:33.690 --> 01:07:36.064
SCOOTER BRAUN: He's got to
show up at my pickup game now.

01:07:36.064 --> 01:07:39.060
AUDIENCE: Yeah, and there's
not too much overlap today.

01:07:39.060 --> 01:07:41.070
Curious-- you said
that Facebook was

01:07:41.070 --> 01:07:43.770
kind of like the one that
got away on the tech side.

01:07:43.770 --> 01:07:46.544
Curious if there's something
on the artist side--

01:07:46.544 --> 01:07:47.460
oh, I saw this person.

01:07:47.460 --> 01:07:48.835
They didn't come with me.

01:07:48.835 --> 01:07:51.210
SCOOTER BRAUN: I mean, there's
a bunch of different ones.

01:07:51.210 --> 01:07:52.626
But I really--
it's like Facebook.

01:07:52.626 --> 01:07:53.550
I don't have a regret.

01:07:53.550 --> 01:07:55.630
I feel like it just led
me one way to another.

01:07:55.630 --> 01:07:59.430
I mean, a funny story is I knew
Macklemore before he blew up.

01:07:59.430 --> 01:08:01.710
We were friends, and I
knew about him in Seattle.

01:08:01.710 --> 01:08:04.860
And he had the mix tape, and
it was just all the hits.

01:08:04.860 --> 01:08:05.990
But it wasn't out yet.

01:08:05.990 --> 01:08:06.865
And he sent it to me.

01:08:06.865 --> 01:08:07.930
We were talking.

01:08:07.930 --> 01:08:09.780
And I was just like,
is there any way

01:08:09.780 --> 01:08:12.054
I can get you to sign over here?

01:08:12.054 --> 01:08:14.220
And he said, look, the only
person I would sign with

01:08:14.220 --> 01:08:15.540
is Drake.

01:08:15.540 --> 01:08:17.195
So I hit up Drake.

01:08:17.195 --> 01:08:18.569
And I'm like, you
should do this.

01:08:18.569 --> 01:08:19.439
And he's like, OK, hit.

01:08:19.439 --> 01:08:21.189
And he tells me one
of his guys, you know,

01:08:21.189 --> 01:08:23.330
to hit-- who he trusts
on the A&amp;R side.

01:08:23.330 --> 01:08:27.710
And Drake and I weren't in
business the way we are now,

01:08:27.710 --> 01:08:28.740
but we were friends.

01:08:28.740 --> 01:08:31.729
And his guy just didn't
pay attention and passed.

01:08:31.729 --> 01:08:34.229
And when Macklemore's album
went number one, they were like,

01:08:34.229 --> 01:08:35.789
don't tell Drake.

01:08:35.789 --> 01:08:38.939
[LAUGHTER]

01:08:38.939 --> 01:08:42.689
But, like I said, I wake
up and I look at my life.

01:08:42.689 --> 01:08:44.700
I don't want to look
back and have regrets.

01:08:44.700 --> 01:08:46.075
I think the only
thing you should

01:08:46.075 --> 01:08:49.020
have regret about is things
that you do that were malicious.

01:08:49.020 --> 01:08:51.300
Missing out on stuff
or anything like that,

01:08:51.300 --> 01:08:52.859
I don't have regrets.

01:08:52.859 --> 01:08:54.520
That's part of the journey.

01:08:54.520 --> 01:08:56.340
But if you do
something malicious--

01:08:56.340 --> 01:08:59.200
I'll tell you something
I have regret about.

01:08:59.200 --> 01:09:02.350
I was at basketball camp when I
was in seventh grade or eighth

01:09:02.350 --> 01:09:04.089
grade-- like sleep away camp--

01:09:04.089 --> 01:09:06.130
and these older kids, a
year older than me-- they

01:09:06.130 --> 01:09:06.970
were real cool.

01:09:06.970 --> 01:09:08.386
They were like,
come hang with us.

01:09:08.386 --> 01:09:09.819
Because I was good.

01:09:09.819 --> 01:09:13.390
And they were like, man, this
kid in our hall, he's a dork.

01:09:13.390 --> 01:09:14.470
And I'm like, dork--

01:09:14.470 --> 01:09:14.979
I'm a dork.

01:09:14.979 --> 01:09:16.982
But OK.

01:09:16.982 --> 01:09:19.065
And they broke into his
room while he wasn't there

01:09:19.065 --> 01:09:20.815
and they put all his
shorts on the ground.

01:09:20.815 --> 01:09:23.050
They're like,
Scooter, pee on it.

01:09:23.050 --> 01:09:24.285
And I knew it was wrong.

01:09:24.285 --> 01:09:26.160
But these older kids
were peer pressuring me,

01:09:26.160 --> 01:09:28.200
and I peed on this
poor kid's clothes.

01:09:31.439 --> 01:09:32.970
The camp-- it gets reported.

01:09:32.970 --> 01:09:36.300
Kid's having to wear his
bathing suit to play and stuff,

01:09:36.300 --> 01:09:37.649
because there's pee.

01:09:37.649 --> 01:09:39.790
And I just felt so bad.

01:09:39.790 --> 01:09:42.337
I was like, screw these kids.

01:09:42.337 --> 01:09:44.420
So I went up to him and I
said, I did this to you.

01:09:44.420 --> 01:09:45.240
I'm so sorry.

01:09:45.240 --> 01:09:46.290
Screw these kids.

01:09:46.290 --> 01:09:47.250
I reported myself.

01:09:47.250 --> 01:09:48.750
They didn't let me play
in the all-star game

01:09:48.750 --> 01:09:50.040
even though I had
made the all-star team

01:09:50.040 --> 01:09:51.330
at the end of the week.

01:09:51.330 --> 01:09:54.870
And to this day, even
though I made it right,

01:09:54.870 --> 01:09:57.480
kind of, I never
forgot that, because I

01:09:57.480 --> 01:09:58.620
was like, that's regret.

01:09:58.620 --> 01:09:59.820
I knew better.

01:09:59.820 --> 01:10:01.350
I shouldn't have done that.

01:10:01.350 --> 01:10:03.071
But everything else in my life--

01:10:03.071 --> 01:10:04.320
if I missed out, I missed out.

01:10:04.320 --> 01:10:07.788
I didn't do anything bad.

01:10:07.788 --> 01:10:11.300
I shouldn't have peed
on his clothes, man.

01:10:11.300 --> 01:10:14.000
What seventh grader does that?

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:17.360
Also, his mom-- he didn't tell
his mom that we made good--

01:10:17.360 --> 01:10:19.080
so I didn't tell my
dad what happened.

01:10:19.080 --> 01:10:20.740
He didn't understand why I
wasn't in the all-star game.

01:10:20.740 --> 01:10:22.850
And the last day of
camp, the parents come.

01:10:22.850 --> 01:10:23.590
And the mom--

01:10:23.590 --> 01:10:25.090
I'm sitting there,
and she comes up.

01:10:25.090 --> 01:10:26.210
You disgusting little kid.

01:10:26.210 --> 01:10:27.620
How dare you pee on
my son's clothes.

01:10:27.620 --> 01:10:28.220
I'm like, what?

01:10:28.220 --> 01:10:28.670
He's like, no, mom.

01:10:28.670 --> 01:10:29.110
We're good now.

01:10:29.110 --> 01:10:29.520
We're good.

01:10:29.520 --> 01:10:31.103
And my dad's like,
what are you doing?

01:10:31.103 --> 01:10:34.760
And I was like,
I don't know dad.

01:10:34.760 --> 01:10:35.870
[LAUGHTER]

01:10:35.870 --> 01:10:37.640
And then he goes, how
dare you say my son.

01:10:37.640 --> 01:10:38.390
She goes, he peed.

01:10:38.390 --> 01:10:39.230
He goes, he did not pee.

01:10:39.230 --> 01:10:39.590
Tell them!

01:10:39.590 --> 01:10:41.173
And all of the sudden,
he looks at me.

01:10:41.173 --> 01:10:44.560
And I'm like-- and he
goes, oh, you're dead.

01:10:44.560 --> 01:10:46.970
And that was not
a good interaction

01:10:46.970 --> 01:10:49.340
with my dad at that time.

01:10:49.340 --> 01:10:50.910
Coach Braun was
not happy with me.

01:10:53.422 --> 01:10:54.380
AUDIENCE: Hey, Scooter.

01:10:54.380 --> 01:10:57.380
Question-- what are
conversations at the dinner

01:10:57.380 --> 01:10:59.900
table like with your family?

01:10:59.900 --> 01:11:06.950
The Emanuels bring
their work to the table,

01:11:06.950 --> 01:11:09.920
and their narrative reminds me
a lot of your family's as well.

01:11:09.920 --> 01:11:12.154
So I was curious if your
family has a similar--

01:11:12.154 --> 01:11:13.320
SCOOTER BRAUN: So, question.

01:11:13.320 --> 01:11:15.732
Do you want to know what
it was like growing up

01:11:15.732 --> 01:11:16.690
or what is it like now?

01:11:16.690 --> 01:11:18.106
AUDIENCE: Let's
do the growing up.

01:11:18.106 --> 01:11:19.322
SCOOTER BRAUN: Growing up--

01:11:19.322 --> 01:11:20.780
it was very important
to my parents

01:11:20.780 --> 01:11:24.055
that we sat down at the
table and had a family meal.

01:11:24.055 --> 01:11:25.430
And my parents
were 9:00 to 5:00.

01:11:25.430 --> 01:11:27.890
Because my dad was a coach
and then he was a dentist.

01:11:27.890 --> 01:11:29.540
And my mom was an orthodontist.

01:11:29.540 --> 01:11:32.060
So they could be home
every single night

01:11:32.060 --> 01:11:32.854
when work was done.

01:11:32.854 --> 01:11:35.270
And it was always important
for us to sit around the table

01:11:35.270 --> 01:11:36.270
and have a conversation.

01:11:36.270 --> 01:11:39.440
And me and my brother
were very competitive,

01:11:39.440 --> 01:11:42.610
and we'd get into fights because
we were only two years apart.

01:11:42.610 --> 01:11:44.720
But if we fought too much,
then dad got involved,

01:11:44.720 --> 01:11:48.650
and he was bigger and
stronger and fights better.

01:11:48.650 --> 01:11:52.970
But it was very much challenges,
extremely competitive

01:11:52.970 --> 01:11:53.660
challenges.

01:11:53.660 --> 01:11:55.790
Me and my dad were
definitely the loudest.

01:11:55.790 --> 01:11:58.790
My mom, when she spoke,
everyone shut up and listened,

01:11:58.790 --> 01:12:01.110
because she was the quiet boss.

01:12:01.110 --> 01:12:05.010
My dad would talk a lot, but if
my mom spoke, it was like, OK.

01:12:05.010 --> 01:12:08.120
We're done now.

01:12:08.120 --> 01:12:10.160
